Chlorobenzene has a melting point of -45 °C, reflecting the influence of the electron-withdrawing chlorine substituent on the benzene ring. Aliphatic substituents on the nitrogen could reduce the effect of hydrogen bonding slightly. The -N(C)2 group's electron-donating effect might raise the melting point further by enhancing the electron cloud density around the aromatic ring, although its steric hindrance may negate some hydrogen bonding. The amide functional group (C=O) also typically raises the melting point due to its ability to participate in hydrogen bonding and its dipolar character. Let's consider the following adjustments to the base structure of chlorobenzene: Increase for amide functionality: +100 °C, Increase for di-substituted urea functionality: +120 °C, Slight decrease for steric hindrance and decreased hydrogen bonding due to N(C)2 group: -20 °C.
